// Annotated excerpt for s05. The upstream file is plain JSON (212 lines,
// 10 lifecycle events). This teaching copy is JSONC — "//"-prefixed
// commentary added BY THIS PROJECT for pedagogy. The upstream file does
// NOT contain comments; do not paste this back as-is.
//
// Lines below mirror upstream L1–L62 (the UserPromptSubmit and
// SessionStart blocks). They are the two shapes we parse in hook.go:
//   - one matcher per entry, "*" wildcards (UserPromptSubmit L4–L19);
//   - multiple matchers per event, each with its own timeout
//     (SessionStart L21–L62 — *, init, maintenance).
{
  // L1–L3 — top-level envelope. The dispatcher ignores "description".
  "description": "OMC orchestration hooks with async capabilities",
  "hooks": {
    // ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // L4–L19 — UserPromptSubmit. Single "*" matcher. Two hooks fire
    // concurrently in upstream (Promise.allSettled); the Go port walks
    // them serially in declaration order but isolates failures.
    "UserPromptSubmit": [
      {
        "matcher": "*",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "node \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/run.cjs \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/keyword-detector.mjs",
            "timeout": 5
          },
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "node \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/run.cjs \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/skill-injector.mjs",
            "timeout": 3
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    // ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // L21–L62 — SessionStart. Three entries, three matchers. The "init"
    // and "maintenance" matchers fire ONLY when the runtime payload's
    // matcher field equals that string (upstream uses an exact match;
    // the Go port uses substring against the raw payload bytes — close
    // enough for teaching, see dispatcher.go::matches commentary).
    "SessionStart": [
      {
        "matcher": "*",                      // always fires
        "hooks": [
          { "type": "command",
            "command": "node \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/run.cjs \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/session-start.mjs",
            "timeout": 5 },
          { "type": "command",
            "command": "node \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/run.cjs \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/project-memory-session.mjs",
            "timeout": 5 },
          { "type": "command",
            "command": "node \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/run.cjs \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/wiki-session-start.mjs",
            "timeout": 5 }
        ]
      },
      {
        "matcher": "init",                   // first run only
        "hooks": [
          { "type": "command",
            "command": "node \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/run.cjs \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/setup-init.mjs",
            "timeout": 30 }
        ]
      },
      {
        "matcher": "maintenance",            // weekly upkeep
        "hooks": [
          { "type": "command",
            "command": "node \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/run.cjs \"$CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT\"/scripts/setup-maintenance.mjs",
            "timeout": 60 }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}

// Reading notes (Go-port comparisons):
//
// 1. **L4–L19 (UserPromptSubmit) → testdata/hooks.json + Dispatcher.**
//    The shape is "event: [{matcher, hooks: [...]}, ...]" — exactly what
//    type Manifest map[string][]Entry encodes. The two-hook concurrent
//    fire becomes a serial in-order walk in Go; we lose the latency win
//    but keep the deterministic ordering tests need.
// 2. **Timeouts are in seconds, on disk.** Upstream relies on the JS
//    runtime's number-to-ms convention; the Go port has no such
//    convention, so hook.go::UnmarshalJSON multiplies by time.Second
//    explicitly. Drop that helper and the field becomes 5 nanoseconds.
// 3. **"matcher": "*" vs. named.** Upstream uses a tiny regex/string
//    matcher inside a wrapper. We lift it to substring-against-payload
//    so a payload of {"reason":"init"} fires the SessionStart/init
//    entry without parsing the JSON twice. This is faithful enough for
//    teaching; production would parse the payload and extract the
//    matcher field properly.
// 4. **timeout: 1 → 60 range.** Upstream timeouts cluster in 3–60s.
//    Short hooks (keyword-detector) run in 5s; setup-init gets 30; the
//    weekly maintenance script gets 60. The teaching manifest uses 1s
//    for the boulder/sleep_too_long case so the timeout test runs in
//    one second instead of waiting on real upstream defaults.
// 5. **Why we copy this file even though it's already JSON.** Plan
//    §"Required reading" calls for an annotated excerpt. JSON has no
//    standard comment syntax; we use JSONC purely as the annotation
//    medium. The teaching repo's actual on-disk fixture
//    (testdata/hooks.json) is plain JSON so encoding/json parses it
//    without a JSONC dependency.
// 6. **What we leave out.** PreToolUse, PermissionRequest, PostToolUse,
//    PostToolUseFailure, SubagentStart/Stop, PreCompact, Stop,
//    SessionEnd — eight more event types, all the same shape. The
//    Manifest map is permissive: any new event name "just works"
//    without touching the dispatcher.
